{"title_page": "Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish chess player}}\n{{Infobox chess player\n| name = Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez\n| image = Juan Manuel Bellon Lopez Rilton Cup 2009.jpg\n| birthname = \n| caption = Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez in 2009\n| country = [[Spain]]<br>[[Sweden]]\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1950|5|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Valencia]], [[Spain]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = \n| children =\n| title = [[FIDE titles|Grandmaster (GM)]] (1978)\n| worldchampion = \n| womensworldchampion = \n| peakrating =\n| FideID = 2200031\n}}\n\n'''Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez''' (born 8 May 1950) is a [[Spain|Spanish]] and [[Sweden|Swedish]] (from 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ratings.fide.com/fedchange.phtml?year=2017|title=FIDE Player transfers|website=ratings.fide.com}}</ref>) [[chess]] [[FIDE titles|Grandmaster]] (1978), five-times [[Spanish Chess Championship]] winner (1969, 1971, 1974, 1977, 1982), [[Chess Olympiad]] individual silver medal winner ([[23rd Chess Olympiad|1978]]), and [[European Team Chess Championship]] (1989) individual bronze medal winner.\n\n==Biography==\nFrom the late 1960s to the mid-1990s, Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez was one of the top Spanish chess players. In 1969, 1971, 1974, 1977 and 1982 he won [[Spanish Chess Championship]] five times. Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez has participated in international chess tournaments many times, achieving successes including first place or shared first place in: [[Stockholm]] ''Rilton Cup'' (1986/87), [[Barcelona]] (1988), [[Terrassa]] (1990), [[Castell-Platja d'Aro]] (1994), [[Santa Clara, Cuba|Santa Clara]] (1999), [[Varadero]] (2000).\n\nJuan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez played for Spain in the [[Chess Olympiad]]s:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olimpbase.org/players/66wsek8p.html|title=OlimpBase :: Men's Chess Olympiads :: Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref>\n* In 1970, at second reserve board in the [[19th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Siegen]] (+4, =1, -4),\n* In 1972, at first reserve board in the [[20th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Skopje]] (+7, =3, -3),\n* In 1974, at fourth board in the [[21st Chess Olympiad]] in [[Nice]] (+7, =8, -3),\n* In 1976, at second board in the [[22nd Chess Olympiad]] in [[Haifa]] (+6, =1, -4),\n* In 1978, at fourth board in the [[23rd Chess Olympiad]] in [[Buenos Aires]] (+8, =4, -1) and won individual silver medal,\n* In 1980, at second board in the [[24th Chess Olympiad]] in [[La Valletta]] (+6, =3, -4),\n* In 1982, at second board in the [[25th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Lucerne]] (+3, =3, -4),\n* In 1984, at second board in the [[26th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Thessaloniki]] (+1, =4, -5),\n* In 1986, at third board in the [[27th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Dubai]] (+2, =2, -2),\n* In 1988, at fourth board in the [[28th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Thessaloniki]] (+2, =1, -4),\n* In 1992, at third board in the [[30th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Manila]] (+4, =3, -4).\n\nJuan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez played for Spain in the [[European Team Chess Championship]]s:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olimpbase.org/playerse/66wsek8p.html|title=OlimpBase :: European Men's Team Chess Championship :: Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref>\n* In 1970, at fifth board in the 4th European Team Chess Championship in [[Kapfenberg]] (+0, =1, -5),\n* In 1989, at second board in the 9th European Team Chess Championship in [[Haifa]] (+4, =3, -1) and won individual bronze medal.\n\nAlso Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez three times participated in [[Clare Benedict Cup|Clare Benedict Chess Cup]] (1970, 1974-1977) and in team competition won gold (1970) medal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olimpbase.org/playersq/66wsek8p.html|title=OlimpBase :: Clare Benedict Chess Cup :: Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, he was awarded the FIDE International Master (IM) title and received the FIDE Grandmaster (GM) title four years later. Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez is also a FIDE Developmental Instructor (2014).\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is [[List of chess families|married]] to Swedish chess grandmaster [[Pia Cramling]] and their daughter Anna Cramling Bellon (born 2002) is Woman FIDE Master.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ratings.fide.com/card.phtml?event=32009232|title=Cramling Bellon, Anna FIDE Chess Profile - Players Arbiters Trainers|website=ratings.fide.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{chessgames player|id=15394}}\n*[https://www.365chess.com/players/Juan_Manuel_Bellon_Lopez Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez] chess games at 365chess.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez, Juan Manuel}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Valencia]]\n[[Category:Spanish chess players]]\n[[Category:Swedish chess players]]\n[[Category:Chess grandmasters]]\n[[Category:Chess Olympiad competitors]]\n\n{{Spain-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish chess player}}\n{{Infobox chess player\n| name = Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez\n| image = Juan Manuel Bellon Lopez Rilton Cup 2009.jpg\n| birthname = \n| caption = Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez in 2009\n| country = [[Spain]]<br>[[Sweden]]\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1950|5|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Valencia]], [[Spain]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = \n| children =\n| title = [[FIDE titles|Grandmaster (GM)]] (1978)\n| worldchampion = \n| womensworldchampion = \n| peakrating =\n| FideID = 2200031\n}}\n\n'''Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez''' (born 8 May 1950) is a [[Spain|Spanish]] and [[Sweden|Swedish]] (from 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ratings.fide.com/fedchange.phtml?year=2017|title=FIDE Player transfers|website=ratings.fide.com}}</ref>) [[chess]] [[FIDE titles|Grandmaster]] (1978), five-times [[Spanish Chess Championship]] winner (1969, 1971, 1974, 1977, 1982), [[Chess Olympiad]] individual silver medal winner ([[23rd Chess Olympiad|1978]]), [[European Team Chess Championship]] (1989) individual bronze medal winner.\n\n==Biography==\nFrom the late 1960s to the mid-1990s, Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez was one of the top Spanish chess players. In 1969, 1971, 1974, 1977 and 1982 he won [[Spanish Chess Championship]] five times. Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez has participated in international chess tournaments many times, achieving successes including first place or shared first place in: [[Stockholm]] ''Rilton Cup'' (1986/87), [[Barcelona]] (1988), [[Terrassa]] (1990), [[Castell-Platja d'Aro]] (1994), [[Santa Clara, Cuba|Santa Clara]] (1999), [[Varadero]] (2000).\n\nJuan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez played for Spain in the [[Chess Olympiad]]s:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olimpbase.org/players/66wsek8p.html|title=OlimpBase :: Men's Chess Olympiads :: Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref>\n* In 1970, at second reserve board in the [[19th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Siegen]] (+4, =1, -4),\n* In 1972, at first reserve board in the [[20th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Skopje]] (+7, =3, -3),\n* In 1974, at fourth board in the [[21st Chess Olympiad]] in [[Nice]] (+7, =8, -3),\n* In 1976, at second board in the [[22nd Chess Olympiad]] in [[Haifa]] (+6, =1, -4),\n* In 1978, at fourth board in the [[23rd Chess Olympiad]] in [[Buenos Aires]] (+8, =4, -1) and won individual silver medal,\n* In 1980, at second board in the [[24th Chess Olympiad]] in [[La Valletta]] (+6, =3, -4),\n* In 1982, at second board in the [[25th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Lucerne]] (+3, =3, -4),\n* In 1984, at second board in the [[26th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Thessaloniki]] (+1, =4, -5),\n* In 1986, at third board in the [[27th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Dubai]] (+2, =2, -2),\n* In 1988, at fourth board in the [[28th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Thessaloniki]] (+2, =1, -4),\n* In 1992, at third board in the [[30th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Manila]] (+4, =3, -4).\n\nJuan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez played for Spain in the [[European Team Chess Championship]]s:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olimpbase.org/playerse/66wsek8p.html|title=OlimpBase :: European Men's Team Chess Championship :: Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref>\n* In 1970, at fifth board in the 4th European Team Chess Championship in [[Kapfenberg]] (+0, =1, -5),\n* In 1989, at second board in the 9th European Team Chess Championship in [[Haifa]] (+4, =3, -1) and won individual bronze medal.\n\nAlso Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez three times participated in [[Clare Benedict Cup|Clare Benedict Chess Cup]] (1970, 1974-1977) and in team competition won gold (1970) medal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olimpbase.org/playersq/66wsek8p.html|title=OlimpBase :: Clare Benedict Chess Cup :: Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, he was awarded the FIDE International Master (IM) title and received the FIDE Grandmaster (GM) title four years later. Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez is also a FIDE Developmental Instructor (2014).\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is [[List of chess families|married]] to Swedish chess grandmaster [[Pia Cramling]] and their daughter Anna Cramling Bellon (born 2002) is Woman FIDE Master.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ratings.fide.com/card.phtml?event=32009232|title=Cramling Bellon, Anna FIDE Chess Profile - Players Arbiters Trainers|website=ratings.fide.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{chessgames player|id=15394}}\n*[https://www.365chess.com/players/Juan_Manuel_Bellon_Lopez Juan Manuel Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez] chess games at 365chess.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bell\u00f3n L\u00f3pez, Juan Manuel}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Valencia]]\n[[Category:Spanish chess players]]\n[[Category:Swedish chess players]]\n[[Category:Chess grandmasters]]\n[[Category:Chess Olympiad competitors]]\n\n{{Spain-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Manuel_Bell%C3%B3n_L%C3%B3pez"}
{"title_page": "Rodrigues Lima", "text_new": "{{short description|First Elected Governor of Bahia}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{more citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{more footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n\n{{Expand language|topic=|langcode=pt|otherarticle=Rodrigues Lima|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix    = \n| name                = Rodrigues Lima\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific_suffix    = \n| image               = Rodrigues Lima.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| image_upright       = \n| smallimage          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Rodrigues Lima, c. 1900.\n| office              = \n| term_start          = 1892\n| term_end            = 1896\n| predecessor         = [[Leal Ferreira]]\n| successor           = [[Lu\u00eds Viana]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1845|05|04}}\n| birth_place         = [[Caetit\u00e9]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1903|12|18|1845|05|04}}\n| death_place         = [[Caetit\u00e9]]\n| alma_mater      = [[Faculty of Medicine of Bahia]]\n| nationality         = {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Brazilian]]\n| spouse              = Maria Victoria Gomes of Albuquerque Lima\n| parents             = Mother: Rita Sofia Gomes de Lima\n*\nFather: Joaquim Manoel Rodrigues Lima (father)\n| profession      = [[Doctor]]\n| serviceyears    = 1866-1869\n}}\n'''Joaquim Manuel Rodrigues Lima''' (Birth and Death:May 4, 1845 \u2013 December 18, 1903)was a [[Physician|Brazilian physician]] and [[politician]] who served in the [[Paraguayan War]] and was an attorney in the hometown and ruled the state of [[Bahia]].\n\n== Biography ==\nHe was the son of '''Captain Joaquim Manuel Rodrigues Lima''' and '''Rita Sofia Gomes de Lima''' (sister of the [[Baron of Caetit\u00e9]]).\n\nAt the age of ten he went to study in [[Salvador]] and in [[1862]] he entered the Medical School of the capital of Bahia and, attending the 5th year, serves in the blood hospitals of the [[Paraguayan War]], as a surgeon. He survived, with heroism,<ref>During this episode, he acted with a denode in the rescue and protection of the gold that the vessel carried for the cost of the campaign, on which success depended: the epithet of heroic action was then in recognition of his denode in military action.</ref> the sinking of the ship that was driving him to Uruguay. In [[1868]], after returning completes the medical course.<ref>{{cit web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303183552/http://www.fameb.ufba.br/dmdocuments/formadosfmb1812a2007.pdf|title=Nominal Survey of Graduates from 1812 to 2008 of the Faculty of Medicine of Bahia - UFBA. (PDF). Faculty of Medicine of Bahia. 2009. Consulted on 16 November 2016. Filed from the original (PDF) on March 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nReturning to Caetit\u00e9, he married the firstborn of the Baron of Caetit\u00e9 and his cousin, D. Maria Victoria Gomes de Albuquerque Lima. He practices the clinic, takes care of the farms and begins in politics, being elected three times to the Provincial Assembly. \nIn 1876-77 he made extensive study trips throughout Europe.\n\nAt the time of the [[Proclamation of the Republic (Brazil)|Proclamation of the Republic]] was the president of the City Council (the City Council, at the time). In 1891,when political parties are organized, he occupied the Municipal Intendency, being nominated for the State Constituent Assembly, where he proposed the change of the capital to [[Vit\u00f3ria da Conquista]].\n\nAfter the resignation of the intervenor [[Jos\u00e9 Moura Gon\u00e7alves|Jos\u00e9 Gon\u00e7alves]], had his name indicated to be the first elected president of the history of Bahia, in an election in which he obtains an overwhelming majority. After his rule, he returned to his homeland, where he still occupies the truth. He dies as one of the most progressive spirits in his city as one of the most progressive spirits in his city.\n\n== Government of Bahia ==\nHis administration was marked by administrative restructuring, a total incentive to culture and education, marked mainly by probity (he wrote several times to his attorney in Caetit\u00e9 to send him money, because he did not think it was honest to avail himself of the public treasury to keep up). Several cultural institutions had their support to constitute themselves, among which the [[Bahia|Geographic and Historical Institute of Bahia]].\n\nRodrigues Lima also spread public works throughout the state, especially those to combat the effects of droughts (many of them existing to date), and by the internalization of quality education.\n\nIn Salvador he carries out several works, aiming to modernize and beautify the Capital: the most beautiful square in the city, [[Campo Grande]], a tourist attraction that honors the heroes of Bahian Independence, is the work of his government.\n\n== Tributes ==\n''Largo da Vit\u00f3ria'', in Salvador, bears a bust in his honor. Pedro Celestino da Silva notes that this monument was initially erected in The Aclamation Square, and was later moved to the square. It also records that this was given as \"a preito of longing and gratitude to the beneficent citizen who, by his civic and private virtues, left his name entirely linked to the history of Bahia, for his immaculate honor, for his greatness of mind and for his unfailing political loyalty\". The monument was authorized by municipal resolution no. 144 of January 4, 1905 and inaugurated on May 13, 1911,by governor Jo\u00e3o Ferreira de Ara\u00fajo Pinho and intendant (mayor) Ant\u00f4nio Carneiro da Rocha. The monument bears the following inscription: ''\"Dr. in Medicine by the Faculty of Bahia; volunteer of the Paraguayan Health Corps;. provincial deputy; state senator; member of the Constituent; Intendant of the Municipality of Caetit\u00e9, where he resided, and Governor of this State.\"''<ref>SILVA, Pedro Celestino da. Historical and Geographical News of the Municipality of Caetit\u00e9, magazine of the Geographic and Historical Institute of [[Bahia]], ''vol. 58, 1932, pp. 266 to 270''</ref>\n\nIt is the name of several places in Bahia, especially in [[Len\u00e7\u00f3is]] and [[Caetit\u00e9]].\n\n== Sources ==\n*{{cite web|url=http://brazil.crl.edu/bsd/bsd/u1918/index.html|title=Message and reports submitted to the Legislative General Assembly by Dr. '''Joaquim Manuel Rodrigues Lima''', governor of the state, on April 7, 1893}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://brazil.crl.edu/bsd/bsd/u012/000602.html|title=Message from the exmo. Dr. Governor of the State (Joaquim Manuel Rodrigues Lima), addressed to the General Assembly, at the 2nd session of the 2nd legislature, on April 7, 1894}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://brazil.crl.edu/bsd/bsd/u013/index.html|title=Message presented to the General Legislative Assembly by Dr. '''Joaquim Manuel Rodrigues Lima''', governor of the state, on April 7, 1896}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1903 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|First Elected Governor of Bahia}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{more citations needed|date=April 2020}}}}\n{{more footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand language|topic=|langcode=pt|otherarticle=Rodrigues Lima|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix    = \n| name                = Rodrigues Lima\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific_suffix    = \n| image               = Rodrigues Lima.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| image_upright       = \n| smallimage          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Rodrigues Lima, c. 1900.\n| office              = \n| term_start          = 1892\n| term_end            = 1896\n| predecessor         = [[Leal Ferreira]]\n| successor           = [[Lu\u00eds Viana]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1845|05|04}}\n| birth_place         = [[Caetit\u00e9]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1903|12|18|1845|05|04}}\n| death_place         = [[Caetit\u00e9]]\n| alma_mater      = [[Faculty of Medicine of Bahia]]\n| nationality         = {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Brazilian]]\n| spouse              = Maria Victoria Gomes of Albuquerque Lima\n| parents             = Mother: Rita Sofia Gomes de Lima\n*\nFather: Joaquim Manoel Rodrigues Lima (father)\n| profession      = [[Doctor]]\n| serviceyears    = 1866-1869\n}}\n'''Joaquim Manuel Rodrigues Lima''' (Birth and Death:May 4, 1845 \u2013 December 18, 1903)was a [[Physician|Brazilian physician]] and [[Politician|politician]] who served in the [[Paraguayan War]] and was an attorney in the hometown and ruled the state of [[Bahia]].\n\n== Biography ==\nHe was the son of '''Captain Joaquim Manuel Rodrigues Lima''' and '''Rita Sofia Gomes de Lima''' (sister of the [[Baron of Caetit\u00e9]]).\n\nAt the age of ten he went to study in [[Salvador]] and in [[1862]] he entered the Medical School of the capital of Bahia and, attending the 5th year, serves in the blood hospitals of the [[Paraguayan War]], as a surgeon. He survived, with heroism,<ref>During this episode, he acted with a denode in the rescue and protection of the gold that the vessel carried for the cost of the campaign, on which success depended: the epithet of heroic action was then in recognition of his denode in military action.</ref> the sinking of the ship that was driving him to Uruguay. In [[1868]], after returning completes the medical course.<ref>{{cit web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303183552/http://www.fameb.ufba.br/dmdocuments/formadosfmb1812a2007.pdf|title=Nominal Survey of Graduates from 1812 to 2008 of the Faculty of Medicine of Bahia - UFBA. (PDF). Faculty of Medicine of Bahia. 2009. Consulted on 16 November 2016. Filed from the original (PDF) on March 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nReturning to Caetit\u00e9, he married the firstborn of the Baron of Caetit\u00e9 and his cousin, D. Maria Victoria Gomes de Albuquerque Lima. He practices the clinic, takes care of the farms and begins in politics, being elected three times to the Provincial Assembly. \nIn 1876-77 he made extensive study trips throughout Europe.\n\nAt the time of the [[Proclamation of the Republic (Brazil)|Proclamation of the Republic]] was the president of the City Council (the City Council, at the time). In 1891,when political parties are organized, he occupied the Municipal Intendency, being nominated for the State Constituent Assembly, where he proposed the change of the capital to [[Vit\u00f3ria da Conquista]].\n\nAfter the resignation of the intervenor [[Jos\u00e9 Moura Gon\u00e7alves|Jos\u00e9 Gon\u00e7alves]], had his name indicated to be the first elected president of the history of Bahia, in a election in which he obtains an overwhelming majority. After his rule, he returned to his homeland, where he still occupies the truth. He dies as one of the most progressive spirits in his city as one of the most progressive spirits in his city.\n\n== Government of Bahia ==\nHis administration was marked by administrative restructuring, a total incentive to culture and education, marked mainly by probity (he wrote several times to his attorney in Caetit\u00e9 to send him money, because he did not think it was honest to avail himself of the public treasury to keep up). Several cultural institutions had their support to constitute themselves, among which the [[Bahia|Geographic and Historical Institute of Bahia]].\n\nRodrigues Lima also spread public works throughout the state, especially those to combat the effects of droughts (many of them existing to date), and by the internalization of quality education.\n\nIn Salvador he carries out several works, aiming to modernize and beautify the Capital: the most beautiful square in the city, [[Campo Grande]], a tourist attraction that honors the heroes of Bahian Independence, is the work of his government.\n\n== Tributes ==\n''Largo da Vit\u00f3ria'', in Salvador, bears a bust in his honor. Pedro Celestino da Silva notes that this monument was initially erected in The Aclamation Square, and was later moved to the square. It also records that this was given as \"a preito of longing and gratitude to the beneficent citizen who, by his civic and private virtues, left his name entirely linked to the history of Bahia, for his immaculate honor, for his greatness of mind and for his unfailing political loyalty\". The monument was authorized by municipal resolution no. 144 of January 4, 1905 and inaugurated on May 13, 1911,by governor Jo\u00e3o Ferreira de Ara\u00fajo Pinho and intendant (mayor) Ant\u00f4nio Carneiro da Rocha. The monument bears the following inscription: ''\"Dr. in Medicine by the Faculty of Bahia; volunteer of the Paraguayan Health Corps;. provincial deputy; state senator; member of the Constituent; Intendant of the Municipality of Caetit\u00e9, where he resided, and Governor of this State.\"''<ref>SILVA, Pedro Celestino da. Historical and Geographical News of the Municipality of Caetit\u00e9, magazine of the Geographic and Historical Institute of [[Bahia]], ''vol. 58, 1932, pp. 266 to 270''</ref>\n\nIt is the name of several places in Bahia, especially in [[Len\u00e7\u00f3is]] and [[Caetit\u00e9]].\n\n== Sources ==\n*{{cite web|url=http://brazil.crl.edu/bsd/bsd/u1918/index.html|title=Message and reports submitted to the Legislative General Assembly by Dr. '''Joaquim Manuel Rodrigues Lima''', governor of the state, on April 7, 1893}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://brazil.crl.edu/bsd/bsd/u012/000602.html|title=Message from the exmo. Dr. Governor of the State (Joaquim Manuel Rodrigues Lima), addressed to the General Assembly, at the 2nd session of the 2nd legislature, on April 7, 1894}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://brazil.crl.edu/bsd/bsd/u013/index.html|title=Message presented to the General Legislative Assembly by Dr. '''Joaquim Manuel Rodrigues Lima''', governor of the state, on April 7, 1896}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Amkgp", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s)