{"title_page": "William A. Harper", "text_new": "'''William A. Harper''' (1873 \u2013 1910) was a Canadian-born artist best known for his landscape paintings, and is represented in both the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City and the National Museum of African American History in Washington, D.C.  Harper was born in the village of Canfield, near Cayuga, Ontario, Canada, and immigrated to Illinois in 1885.  He graduated from the [[Art Institute of Chicago]] (\u201cAIC\u201d) in 1901, and subsequently studied at the Acad\u00e9mie Julian in Paris, France.  Harper\u2019s paintings were regularly accepted in juried exhibitions of the AIC and the Society of Western Artists and were acknowledged with multiple awards.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHarper was born in the village of Canfield, near [[Cayuga, Ontario|Cayuga]], Ontario, Canada, the grandson of escaped slaves<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fragomeni |first1=Carmela |title=Tiny Hamlet Unveils Rich History of Welcoming Runaway Slaves in the 1800s |journal=The Hamilton Spectator, Ontario, Canada |date=September 22, 2017}}</ref>, and immigrated to Illinois in 1885<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite journal |title=Obituary |journal=Bulletin of the Art Institute of Chicago |date=July 1910 |volume=4 |page=11}}</ref> where he attended college in [[Jacksonville, Illinois|Jacksonville]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bentley |first1=Florence L. |title=William A. Harper |journal=The Voice of the Negro |date=January 1906 |volume=3 |page=117}}</ref>  He enrolled in the AIC in 1895, serving as a janitor there to put himself through school. <ref>{{cite journal |title=Home From Paris; Studied Art There |journal=Decatur Daily Review |date=May 6, 1908 |page=7}}</ref>  Harper spent summers working and painting at the [[Eagle's Nest Art Colony]] near Oregon, Illinois where he was the prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of members of the Colony,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Paintings of Note in Art Collection |journal=Ogle County Reporter |date=July 10, 1918 |volume=LXVII |issue=38}}</ref> including Lorado Taft, Charles Francis Browne, and William Wendt.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Simeone |first1=Beth Baker |title=The Art of Oregon |date=2015 |isbn=978-0-9894202-3-5 |pages=54\u201355}}</ref> Harper graduated from the AIC with second honors in 1901.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nHarper accepted a job in Houston, Texas in 1901 as drawing instructor in the Houston public schools.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Increased Enrollement Necessitated the Subscription of Additional Teachers... |journal=Houston Daily Post |date=September 4, 1901 |page=5}}</ref>\n\nIn 1903, he traveled to Europe, initially painting with [[William Wendt]] in Cornwall, England.  In the fall of 1903, Harper enrolled at the [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] in Paris, France, a venue favored by many AIC graduates.  While in Paris, he took the opportunity to copy well-known paintings at the Louvre, and to explore and sketch the French countryside.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Krehbiel |first1=Albert |title=Letters of Albert Krehbiel |journal=Archives of American Art - Smithsonian |date=January 24, 1904}}</ref>  In the spring of 1904, Harper and Charles Francis Browne travelled south of Paris to the area of [[Barbizon]] to paint. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Krehbiel |first1=Albert |title=Letters of Albert Krehbiel |journal=Archives of American Art - Smithsonian |date=March 27, 1904}}</ref>   By 1905, he was back in Chicago, once again working at the AIC to support his painting career, this time as a night watchman.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite journal |title=Chicago Art Echos |journal=American Art News |date=February 25, 1905 |volume=3 |issue=68 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nDuring the years following his graduation from the AIC, Harper\u2019s paintings were regularly accepted in the annual juried exhibition of works by Chicago artists, jointly managed by the AIC and the Municipal Art League of Chicago and in the exhibitions of the Society of Western Artists (of which he was a member).  He won the Municipal Art League prize in 1905<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and the Young Fortnightly Club award in 1908.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Recent Exhibition of Chicago Artists |journal=Bulletin of the Art Institute of Chicago |date=April 1908 |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=35\u201336}}</ref>    Harper\u2019s paintings borne of his time in Cornwall and in France figure prominently in the exhibitions beginning in 1904 and reflect the influence of the Barbizon school on his work.  \n\nHarper made a second trip to France in 1907, this time studying with [[Henry Ossawa Tanner]],<ref name=\"auto\"/> the respected American expatriate artist,  who had homes in both Paris and the north of France.  Harper continued to paint in the French countryside, and under Tanner\u2019s influence his work began to take on a more impressionistic style.  \n\nBy 1908, Harper\u2019s health was failing, and he moved to [[Cuernavaca]], Mexico.<ref name=\"auto\"/>   He nevertheless continued to paint until his death in 1910 from consumption (tuberculosis). Following his death, the AIC featured a one-man exhibition of sixty of Harper\u2019s paintings<ref>{{cite journal |title=Exhibition of Paintings of William A. Harper |journal=The Art Institute of Chicago |date=July 26 \u2013 August 28, 1910}}</ref> , \u201ccertainly the first major museum show for a black artist in Chicago, if not anywhere in the United States.\u201d<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kennedy |first1=Elizabeth |title=Chicago Modern, 1893-1945 |date=2004 |isbn=0-932171-41-9 |page=43}}</ref>\n\n== Museums / Collections ==\n\nHarper\u2019s works appear in numerous museums and important collections including:  \n* Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/694642|title=The Trees, Early Afternoon, France,ca. 1905|website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\n* National Museum of African American History in Washington, Washington, D.C.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nmaahc.si.edu/object/nmaahc_2010.51.1ab?destination=explore/collection/search%3Fedan_q%3Dwilliam%2520a.%2520harper%26edan_local%3D1%26op%3DSearch|title=Untitled (French Landscape)|website=National Museum of African American History and Culture}}</ref>\n* Columbus Museum, Columbus, Georgia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbusmuseum.pastperfectonline.com/webobject/72AC0C4B-7E65-49FB-B641-226254332948|title=Columbus Museum, Painting - Landscape (Brittany)|website=columbusmuseum.pastperfectonline.com|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n* National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nga.gov/collection/artist-info.42623.html|title=Artist Info|website=www.nga.gov|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n* The DuSable Museum of African American History<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dusablemuseum.org/|title=Home|website=DuSable Museum of African American History|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n* Flint Institute of Arts, Flint, Michigan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://flintarts.org/art/objects/3917|title=French Landscape {{!}} Flint Institute of Arts|website=flintarts.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n* Christine M. Schwartz Collection, Chicago, IL<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://schwartzcollection.com/artwork/untitled-landscape-2/|title=Untitled (Landscape)|website=M. Christine Schwartz Collection}}</ref>\n* The Eagle\u2019s Nest Art Collection, Oregon Library, Oregon, Illinois{{cn|date=July 2019}}\n* The Harmon and Harriet Kelley Foundation for The Arts, San Antonio, Texas\n\n For more detailed information on William A. Harper, see: http://www.williamaharper.com/\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harper, William A.}}\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:School of the Art Institute of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian people]]\n[[Category:People from Haldimand County]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of African-American descent]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the  Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Canadian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Artists from Chicago]]\n[[Category:African-American painters]]\n[[Category:American landscape painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in England]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in England]]\n[[Category:People from Cuernavaca]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian landscape painters]]\n", "text_old": "'''William A. Harper''' (1873 \u2013 1910) was a Canadian-born artist best known for his landscape paintings, and is represented in both the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City and the National Museum of African American History in Washington, D.C.  Harper was born in the village of Canfield, near Cayuga, Ontario, Canada, and immigrated to Illinois in 1885.  He graduated from the [[Art Institute of Chicago]] (\u201cAIC\u201d) in 1901, and subsequently studied at the Acad\u00e9mie Julian in Paris, France.  Harper\u2019s paintings were regularly accepted in juried exhibitions of the AIC and the Society of Western Artists and were acknowledged with multiple awards.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHarper was born in the village of Canfield, near [[Cayuga, Ontario|Cayuga]], Ontario, Canada, the grandson of escaped slaves<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fragomeni |first1=Carmela |title=Tiny Hamlet Unveils Rich History of Welcoming Runaway Slaves in the 1800s |journal=The Hamilton Spectator, Ontario, Canada |date=September 22, 2017}}</ref>, and immigrated to Illinois in 1885<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite journal |title=Obituary |journal=Bulletin of the Art Institute of Chicago |date=July 1910 |volume=4 |page=11}}</ref> where he attended college in [[Jacksonville, Illinois|Jacksonville]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bentley |first1=Florence L. |title=William A. Harper |journal=The Voice of the Negro |date=January 1906 |volume=3 |page=117}}</ref>  He enrolled in the AIC in 1895, serving as a janitor there to put himself through school. <ref>{{cite journal |title=Home From Paris; Studied Art There |journal=Decatur Daily Review |date=May 6, 1908 |page=7}}</ref>  Harper spent summers working and painting at the [[Eagle's Nest Art Colony]] near Oregon, Illinois where he was the prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of members of the Colony,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Paintings of Note in Art Collection |journal=Ogle County Reporter |date=July 10, 1918 |volume=LXVII |issue=38}}</ref> including Lorado Taft, Charles Francis Browne, and William Wendt.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Simeone |first1=Beth Baker |title=The Art of Oregon |date=2015 |isbn=978-0-9894202-3-5 |pages=54\u201355}}</ref> Harper graduated from the AIC with second honors in 1901.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nHarper accepted a job in Houston, Texas in 1901 as drawing instructor in the Houston public schools.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Increased Enrollement Necessitated the Subscription of Additional Teachers... |journal=Houston Daily Post |date=September 4, 1901 |page=5}}</ref>\n\nIn 1903, he traveled to Europe, initially painting with [[William Wendt]] in Cornwall, England.  In the fall of 1903, Harper enrolled at the [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] in Paris, France, a venue favored by many AIC graduates.  While in Paris, he took the opportunity to copy well-known paintings at the Louvre, and to explore and sketch the French countryside.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Krehbiel |first1=Albert |title=Letters of Albert Krehbiel |journal=Archives of American Art - Smithsonian |date=January 24, 1904}}</ref>  In the spring of 1904, Harper and Charles Francis Browne travelled south of Paris to the area of [[Barbizon]] to paint. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Krehbiel |first1=Albert |title=Letters of Albert Krehbiel |journal=Archives of American Art - Smithsonian |date=March 27, 1904}}</ref>   By 1905, he was back in Chicago, once again working at the AIC to support his painting career, this time as a night watchman.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite journal |title=Chicago Art Echos |journal=American Art News |date=February 25, 1905 |volume=3 |issue=68 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nDuring the years following his graduation from the AIC, Harper\u2019s paintings were regularly accepted in the annual juried exhibition of works by Chicago artists, jointly managed by the AIC and the Municipal Art League of Chicago and in the exhibitions of the Society of Western Artists (of which he was a member).  He won the Municipal Art League prize in 1905<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and the Young Fortnightly Club award in 1908.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Recent Exhibition of Chicago Artists |journal=Bulletin of the Art Institute of Chicago |date=April 1908 |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=35\u201336}}</ref>    Harper\u2019s paintings borne of his time in Cornwall and in France figure prominently in the exhibitions beginning in 1904 and reflect the influence of the Barbizon school on his work.  \n\nHarper made a second trip to France in 1907, this time studying with [[Henry Ossawa Tanner]],<ref name=\"auto\"/> the respected American expatriate artist,  who had homes in both Paris and the north of France.  Harper continued to paint in the French countryside, and under Tanner\u2019s influence his work began to take on a more impressionistic style.  \n\nBy 1908, Harper\u2019s health was failing, and he moved to [[Cuernavaca]], Mexico.<ref name=\"auto\"/>   He nevertheless continued to paint until his death in 1910 from consumption (tuberculosis). Following his death, the AIC featured a one-man exhibition of sixty of Harper\u2019s paintings<ref>{{cite journal |title=Exhibition of Paintings of William A. Harper |journal=The Art Institute of Chicago |date=July 26 \u2013 August 28, 1910}}</ref> , \u201ccertainly the first major museum show for a black artist in Chicago, if not anywhere in the United States.\u201d<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kennedy |first1=Elizabeth |title=Chicago Modern, 1893-1945 |date=2004 |isbn=0-932171-41-9 |page=43}}</ref>\n\n== Museums / Collections ==\n\nHarper\u2019s works appear in numerous museums and important collections including:  \n* Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/694642|title=The Trees, Early Afternoon, France,ca. 1905|website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\n* National Museum of African American History in Washington, Washington, D.C.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nmaahc.si.edu/object/nmaahc_2010.51.1ab?destination=explore/collection/search%3Fedan_q%3Dwilliam%2520a.%2520harper%26edan_local%3D1%26op%3DSearch|title=Untitled (French Landscape)|website=National Museum of African American History and Culture}}</ref>\n* Columbus Museum, Columbus, Georgia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbusmuseum.pastperfectonline.com/webobject/72AC0C4B-7E65-49FB-B641-226254332948|title=Columbus Museum, Painting - Landscape (Brittany)|website=columbusmuseum.pastperfectonline.com|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n* National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nga.gov/collection/artist-info.42623.html|title=Artist Info|website=www.nga.gov|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n* The DuSable Museum of African American History<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dusablemuseum.org/|title=Home|website=DuSable Museum of African American History|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n* Flint Institute of Arts, Flint, Michigan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://flintarts.org/art/objects/3917|title=French Landscape {{!}} Flint Institute of Arts|website=flintarts.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n* Christine M. Schwartz Collection, Chicago, IL<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://schwartzcollection.com/artwork/untitled-landscape-2/|title=Untitled (Landscape)|website=M. Christine Schwartz Collection}}</ref>\n* The Eagle\u2019s Nest Art Collection, Oregon Library, Oregon, Illinois{{cn|date=July 2019}}\n* Harmon & Harriet Kelley Foundation for the Arts, San Antonio, Texas\n\n For more detailed information on William A. Harper, see: http://www.williamaharper.com/\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harper, William A.}}\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:School of the Art Institute of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian people]]\n[[Category:People from Haldimand County]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of African-American descent]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the  Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Canadian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Artists from Chicago]]\n[[Category:African-American painters]]\n[[Category:American landscape painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in England]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in England]]\n[[Category:People from Cuernavaca]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian landscape painters]]\n", "name_user": "Shoethorn7685", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMuseums / Collections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_A._Harper"}
{"title_page": "The Night of Hate Comments", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{short description|Korean television program}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Night of Hate Comments\n| image                = The Night of Hate Comments.jpg\n| caption              = Promotional poster with original hosts<ref>{{cite web|title=The Night of Hate Comments webpage|url=http://tv.jtbc.joins.com/replynight|date=October 14, 2019|website=[[JTBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014112815/http://tv.jtbc.joins.com/replynight|archivedate=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| show_name_2          = The Night of Vicious Comments,<br />Reply Night\n| native_name          = {{Infobox name module|hangul=\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24}}\n| genre                = [[Variety show]], [[Talk show]]\n| starring             = {{plainlist|\n* [[Shin Dong-yup (comedian)|Shin Dong-yup]]\n* [[Kim Sook (comedian)|Kim Sook]]\n* [[Kim Jong-min]]\n* [[Sulli]]}}\n| country              = South Korea\n| language             = Korean\n| director             = Lee Na-ra<br />Jeong Jae-hoon<br />Chu Mi-rye\n| num_episodes         = 16\n| runtime              = 60 minutes\n| company              = \n| distributor          = [[JTBC]]\n| network              = [[JTBC#Subsidiaries|JTBC2]]\n| picture_format       = [[HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|2019|6|21}}\n| last_aired           = {{end date|2019|10|11}}\n| website              = http://tv.jtbc.joins.com/replynight\n}}\n\n'''''The Night of Hate Comments''''' ({{ko-hhrm|\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24}}), also called '''''The Night of Vicious Comments''''' or '''''Reply Night''''', was a South Korean variety program on [[JTBC#Subsidiaries|JTBC2]] which first aired on June 21, 2019. Through the sixteenth episode, the show's inaugural four hosts, [[Shin Dong-yup (comedian)|Shin Dong-yup]], [[Kim Sook (comedian)|Kim Sook]], [[Kim Jong-min]] and [[Sulli]] welcomed celebrity guest(s) each week to discuss their reactions to hateful comments, malicious rumors, and [[cyberbullying]] they had encountered online. JTBC called it a new show \"to help the stars become stronger psychologically\". The show also brings up proper internet manners and etiquette.<ref>{{cite web|last=June|first=Hae-myoung|title=Sulli's solo comeback befuddles fans|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2019/06/732_270821.html|date=June 18, 2019|work=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=June 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620134044/https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2019/06/732_270821.html|archive-date=June 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"cast\">{{cite web|last=Yoon|first=So-yeon|title=Sulli cast to co-host JTBC talk show|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3063512|date=May 25, 2019|work=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|accessdate=June 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610051830/http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3063512|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Choi|first=Bo-ran|title=\uc2e0\ub3d9\uc5fd\u00b7\uae40\uc219\u00b7\uae40\uc885\ubbfc\u00b7\uc124\ub9ac, \uc545\ud50c\uacfc \ub300\uba74\ud55c\ub2e4...\u65b0\uc608\ub2a5 '\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24'(\uacf5\uc2dd)|url=https://www.ytn.co.kr/_sn/0117_201905241726140596|date=May 24, 2019|work=[[YTN]]|language=Korean|accessdate=June 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525050312/https://www.ytn.co.kr/_sn/0117_201905241726140596|archive-date=May 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The program was discontinued following Sulli's death.<ref name=\"nam\">{{cite news|last1=Nam|first1=Ji-eun|title=\uc124\ub9ac \uc5c6\ub294 \u2018\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24\u2019 \uc885\uc601\ud55c\ub2e4|url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/culture/culture_general/914038.html|accessdate=October 21, 2019|work=[[The Hankyoreh]]|date=October 21, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"jang\">{{cite news|last1=Jang|first1=Woo-young|title='\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24', \uacb0\uad6d \uc885\uc601\u2026\"\u6545 \uc124\ub9ac \ube44\ubcf4 \ud6c4 \uc81c\uc791 \uc911\ub2e8 \uacb0\uc815\" [\uc804\ubb38]|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1111245304|accessdate=October 21, 2019|work=Osen|date=October 21, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe show's producing director is Lee Na-ra who produced another JTBC variety show, ''LAN Cable Life''.<ref name=\"PD\">{{cite web|title=\uc124\ub9ac, \ub4e4\ub7ec\ubd99\ub294 \uc545\uc131\ub313\uae00\uc5d0 \ub2f5\ud55c\ub2e4\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7'\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24'|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2019/05/24/2019052402591.html|date=May 24, 2019|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|language=Korean|accessdate=June 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624080743/http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2019/05/24/2019052402591.html|archive-date=June 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Along with three hosts in their 40s, it was the first long-term hosting role for 25-year-old Sulli and her return to TV work after a number of years.<ref name=\"cast\"/><ref name=\"PD\"/>\n\nThe show's format includes celebrity guests reading and discussing their own [[Social networking service|social media]] comments,<ref name=\"first\">{{cite web|last=Kim|first=Kyeong-young|title=#\uad00\uc885 #\ub178\ube0c\ub77c #\ub9c8\uc57d\u2026'\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24' \uc124\ub9ac \ud5a5\ud55c \uc624\ud574\uc640 \uc9c4\uc2ec\u2192\uc751\uc6d0 ing|url=https://www.ytn.co.kr/_sn/1406_201906221548019643|date=June 22, 2019|work=[[YTN]]|language=Korean|accessdate=June 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624080743/https://www.ytn.co.kr/_sn/1406_201906221548019643|archive-date=June 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and was noted to resemble [[Jimmy Kimmel]]'s ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!#Mean Tweets|Celebrities Read Mean Tweets]]'' by Kang Hae-ryun in the ''[[The Washington Post]]''.<ref name=\"kimmel\">{{cite web|last=Kang|first=Hae-ryun|title=How a K-pop star\u2019s death reveals the truth about our society|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/10/15/how-k-pop-stars-death-reveals-truth-about-our-society/|date=October 16, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=October 16, 2019}}</ref> On the first episode there were no guests and the four hosts set the show's tone, responding to comments about themselves, sometimes acknowledging agreement or disagreement.<ref name=\"first\"/>\n\nOn October 14, 2019, the cast and producers recorded another episode, per a Monday scheduling, unaware of the death of co-host Sulli, which was reported later in the day.<ref name=\"trailers\">{{cite web|last=Kim|first=Young-rok|title=[\uc885\ud569]'\uc545\ud50c\uc758\ubc24' \uc124\ub9ac \uc5c6\uc774 \ub179\ud654\u2192\ucc28\ud6c4 \uacb0\ubc29 \uc720\ub825\u2026\uc608\uace0\ud3b8 \uc774\ubbf8 \uc0ad\uc81c|url=https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2019/10/14/2019101402752.html|date=October 14, 2019|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|language=ko|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref> Trailers and an upcoming episode were immediately cancelled,<ref name=\"trailers\"/><ref name=\"yonhap\">{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Jung-hyun|title=JTBC2 '\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24', \uc124\ub9ac \ube44\ubcf4\uc5d0 \"18\uc77c \ubcf8\ubc29\uc1a1 \ud734\ubc29\"|url=https://www.yna.co.kr/view/AKR20191015119400005|date=October 15, 2019|work=[[Yonhap]]|language=ko|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref> followed by an October 21 announcement that the show would not continue.<ref name=\"nam\"/><ref name=\"jang\"/>\n\n==Reception==\nUpon co-host Sulli's death, some viewers said that the show should be abolished due to the mental anguish it appeared to cause the celebrities as they read and discussed the hateful comments directed at them, and questioned whether such comments might have affected Sulli's psychological state prior to her death.<ref name=\"yonhap\"/><ref name=\"culture\">{{cite web|title=\uc124\ub9ac \ube44\ubcf4\uc5d0 \u2018\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24\u2019 \ud3d0\uc9c0 \ubaa9\uc18c\ub9ac\u2026\u201c\uac00\ud559\uc801 \ubc29\uc1a1\u201d|url=http://www.donga.com/news/List/article/all/20191015/97878786/2|date=October 15, 2019|work=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]]|language=ko|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref> But, others said they felt Sulli participated on the show to fight the culture of cyberbullying and admired her for it; and appreciated the show's efforts.<ref name=\"culture\"/>\n\n==Episode list==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Ep.#\n!Date\n!Guest(s)\n!Name(s)\n!Summary\n!Ref.\n|-\n|rowspan=4|1\n|rowspan=4|June 21\n|rowspan=4 {{N/A|No guest}}\n|Shin Dong-yup\n|There is a comment which says that Shin does not contribute anything to ''Animal Farm'', where animals do all the work and ''[[My Little Old Boy]]'', where mothers do all the work. Hence he is an old guy or \"old fox\" who appears on easy shows; which he disagrees. Another comment mentioned that he always wittily makes inappropriate comments, but he is actually nothing but a successful pervert; which he agrees.\n|rowspan=4|<ref name=\"first\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news1.kr/articles/?3651886|title=\uccab\ubc29 '\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24'\u2026\uc124\ub9ac\uac00 \ubc1d\ud78c #\ub9c8\uc57d #\ub178\ube0c\ub77c #\uc545\ud50c\ub7ec \uace0\uc18c(\uc885\ud569)|date=2019-06-21|website=\ub274\uc2a41|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811150620/http://news1.kr/articles/?3651886|archive-date=August 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvdaily.asiae.co.kr/read.php3?aid=15609934031465999019|title='\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24' \uc124\ub9ac \"\ub0b4 \ud788\ud2b8\uc791 \uc778\uc2a4\ud0c0\uadf8\ub7a8? '\uad00\uc885' \uc778\uc815\"|date=2019-06-20|website=tvdaily.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chuksannews.co.kr/news/article.html?no=184495|title=\u2018\uc545\ud50c\uc758\ubc24\u2019 \uc774\ub0a0 \uc2e0\ub3d9\uc5fd \uae40\uc219 \uae40\uc885\ubbfc \uc124\ub9ac\ub294...|last=\uc8fc\ub2e4\uc601|date=2019-06-25|website=www.chuksannews.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906062315/http://www.chuksannews.co.kr/news/article.html%3Fno%3D184495|archive-date=September 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.joongboo.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=1362662|title='\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24' \uccab\ubc29\ubd80\ud130 \uac15\ud588\ub2e4\u2026 \uc2a4\ud0c0\ub4e4\uc758 \uc545\ud50c \uc140\ud504 \ub0ad\uc1a1 '\uc2e0\uac1c\ub150 \uc608\ub2a5'|date=2019-06-22|website=\uc911\ubd80\uc77c\ubcf4|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623144437/http://www.joongboo.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=1362662|archive-date=June 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Kim Sook\n|One commenter says they are sick of seeing Kim on every show on every channel; which Kim disagrees with. Another comment says she should use dental floss to floss her teeth rather than slicing a watermelon with it.\n|-\n|Kim Jong-min\n|A comment says that Kim does not know the value of the TV licence fee. Another comment says that he dances like \"a wind doll flailing outside a karaoke\".\n|-\n|Sulli\n|One comment says that Sulli's SNS is her biggest success and she is an attention seeker; which she agrees with. Another says that she is a druggie; she disagrees and says that she does not take drugs or do anything illegal.\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2\n|rowspan=3|June 28\n|rowspan=3|[[Song Ga-in]]<br />{{illm|Hong Ja|ko|\ud64d\uc790 (\uac00\uc218)}}<br />{{illm|Park Sung-yeon|ko|\ubc15\uc131\uc5f0}}\n|Song Ga-in\n|One comment says that when she sings, there is no emotion in it and it sounds like a robot. In addition, she will just disappear if she does not release any hit songs. For this hate comment, she did not acknowledge. She did acknowledge another comment which says that she has a typical pig face and she looks like a steamed bun that has been pressed when it is piping hot. She also disagreed with another hate comment asking her if she had a good night's sleep after selecting Hong Ja during the death match on '[[Miss Trot]]'.\n|rowspan=3|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mosen.mt.co.kr/article/G1111174884|title=\"\uc131\ud615? \uc5bb\uc5b4\uac78\ub9b0 \ud64d\uc9c4\uc601\"..'\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24' \ubc15\uc131\uc5f0, \uc124\ub9ac\ub3c4 \uc778\uc815\ud55c \ucfe8\ub140 [\uc885\ud569]|last=OSEN|date=2019-06-29|website=mosen.mt.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903041958/http://mosen.mt.co.kr/article/G1111174884|archive-date=September 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news1.kr/articles/?3655807|title=[N\ucef7] '\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24' \uc1a1\uac00\uc778\u00b7\ud64d\uc790\u00b7\ubc15\uc131\uc5f0, \uc5b4\ub974\uc2e0 \uc2a4\ud0c0\uc77c '\ub77d\ud50c'\uc5d0 \uc5b4\ub9ac\ub465\uc808|date=2019-06-27|website=\ub274\uc2a41|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://isplus.live.joins.com/news/article/article.asp?Total_Id=23510550|title=[\ub9ac\ubdf0IS] \u00b4\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24\u00b4 \uc1a1\uac00\uc778\u00b7\ud64d\uc790\u00b7\ubc15\uc131\uc5f0, \uc545\ud50c\uc5d0\ub3c4 \uad74\ud558\uc9c0 \uc54a\ub294 \uae0d\uc815\u7532|date=2019-09-07|website=isplus.live.joins.com|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629141939/http://isplus.live.joins.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=23510550|archive-date=June 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sports.chosun.com/news/ntype.htm?id=201906290100218590014952&servicedate=20190628|title='\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24' \uc1a1\uac00\uc778 \"\ud788\ud2b8\uace1 \ubabb \ub0b4\uba74 \uc0ac\ub77c\uc9c4\ub2e4\uace0? \ud788\ud2b8\uace1 \ub0bc \uac83\"|date=2019-06-28|website=\uc2a4\ud3ec\uce20\uc870\uc120|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.slist.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=89546|title=\ud64d\uc790 &quot;\ubcf8\uba85\uc740 \ubc15\uc9c0\ubbfc, \uc21c\uc218\ud568\u00b7\uc608\uc068 \ub2f4\uace0 \uc2f6\uc5c8\ub2e4&quot;(\uc545\ud50c\uc758\ubc24) - \uc2f1\uae00\ub9ac\uc2a4\ud2b8|date=2019-06-28|website=www.slist.kr|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://speconomy.com/news/newsview.php?ncode=1065598243702826|title=\ud64d\uc790, \uff02\uc815\ud1b5 \ud2b8\ub85c\ud2b8 \ubabb\ud55c\ub2e4 \uc0dd\uac01 \uc548 \ud574\uff02...\uc545\ud50c\uc5d0 \ubc18\ubc15 \ub4e4\uc5ec\ub2e4\ubcf4\ub2c8?|last=\uc2a4\ud398\uc15c\uacbd\uc81c|date=2019-07-03|website=speconomy.com|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n|-\n|Hong Ja\n|There is a comment saying Hong Ja is just like the name of a [[Makgeolli]] bar owner. Therefore, she will only appeal to middle-aged fans. Another comment also said that she cannot sing traditional trot songs. The other comment also commented that she is kept on sticking with Song Ga-in even after 'Miss Trot' had ended. In addition, the person who wrote the comment also asked why she would do that when she was not at the same level as Song Ga-in. Hong Ja did not acknowledge all the above hate comments.\n|-\n|Park Sung-yeon\n|A comment asked if Sung-yeon has any connection since she did not reach Top 5 on the survival show, but she still appears on TV. Hence, for this statement, she refuted by saying that her company is too small for any connection. Another comment said that she got a full makeover which she agreed and admitted that she indeed went for plastic surgery before her debut. Sung-yeon disagreed the next statement which commented on her teeth being yellow, and said that she should just get them whitened. Lastly, she disagreed another comment pointing on her dancing while singing trot song on an event which ruined the whole trot music.\n|-\n|3\n|July 5\n|[[Jun Jin]] ([[Shinhwa]])<br />{{illm|Kim Seung-hyun (actor)|lt=Kim Seung-hyun|ko|\uae40\uc2b9\ud604 (\ubc30\uc6b0)}}\n|\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sisamagazine.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=210207|title='\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24' 5\uc77c \ubc29\uc1a1\uc5d0\ub294 90\ub144\ub300 \uc808\uce5c \ub77c\uc778... - \uc2dc\uc0ac\ub9e4\uac70\uc9c4|last=\uae30\uc790|first=\uc8fc\uc9c4\ud604|date=1970-01-01|website=www.sisamagazine.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/1137954|title='\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24' \uc804\uc9c4\u00b7\uae40\uc2b9\ud604\uc774 \ubc1d\ud78c #\uacb0\ud63c #\uc5f4\uc560 \uace0\ubc31 #\uc124\ub9ac \ud314\ub85c\uc6b0 [\uc885\ud569]|website=TV\ub9ac\ud3ec\ud2b8|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903024456/https://www.tvreport.co.kr/1137954|archive-date=September 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|4\n|July 12\n|[[Kim Ji-min (comedian)|Kim Ji-min]]<br />[[Sandeul]] ([[B1A4]])\n|\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mosen.mt.co.kr/article/G1111184806|title='\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24' \uc124\ub9ac \"\uacf5\uac1c\uc5f0\uc560 \ud6c4\ud68c \uc548\ud574..\ub9cc\ub098\uba74 \ubc25 \uc0ac\uc8fc\uace0 \uc2f6\ub2e4\"[\ud56bTV]|last=OSEN|date=2019-07-13|website=mosen.mt.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2019-07-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713004724/http://mosen.mt.co.kr/article/G1111184806|archive-date=July 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1140268|title=&quot;'\uc545\ud50c\uc758 \ubc24' \uae40\uc9c0\ubbfcX\uc0b0\ub4e4, \uc678\ubaa8\u2192\uc2e4\ub825 \uc545\ud50c\uae4c\uc9c0\u2026\uc720\ucf8c\ud55c \ub300\ucc98 [\uc885\ud569]|date=2019-07-12|website=www.xportsnews.com|language=ko|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|5\n|rowspan=2|July 19\n|rowspan=2|[[Shin Ji]] ([[Koyote]])<br />{{illm|Seunghee|ko|\uc2b9\ud76c (1996\ub144)}} ([[Oh My Girl]])\n|Shin Ji\n|She disagrees a comment which asked what had she done to make her face so messed up, one side is collapsing, and the other is too firm. It is as if she has those lumps of evil spirts that goblins have. Another comment said that she was a liar to